						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A typical data conversion tool in my NES toolchain is pilbmp2nes.py. Had I made it in Lua instead, I would have run into at least these problems:<br /><br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Tables start at 1, making line-by-line hand translation of programs in other languages that much more error-prone.</li><li>No integer type, instead relying on the FPU. (JavaScript has the same problem.)</li><li>No bitwise operators prior to 5.3. Data converters tend to need them, particular when CHR data and compression are involved.</li><li>Python 3 is installed by default in modern GNU/Linux systems. Lua isn't.<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">The program 'lua' is currently not installed.&nbsp; To run 'lua' please ask your administrator to install the package 'lua5.2'</div></li><li>What's the widely used counterpart to Pillow, the Python imaging library? </li></ol></div><br /><br />It always seems like the ecosystem of a given language has so much to do with which domains it becomes successful in. I have a bunch of python tools as well, I'm very happy with those and will not be rewriting them a third time. Definitely enjoying lua for fceux debugging and also in pico 8 though.</div>

