						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Tables start at 1, making line-by-line hand translation of programs in other languages that much more error-prone.</div><br />I've always found this annoying, but nothing actually stops you from declaring or using index 0:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">local junkPile = {<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&#91;0&#93; = &quot;hello&quot;,<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&#91;1&#93; = &quot;world&quot;,<br />}<br /><br />for k,v in pairs(junkPile) do<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;print(string.format(&quot;&#91;%d&#93; %s&quot;,k,v))<br />end</div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">No integer type, instead relying on the FPU. (JavaScript has the same problem.)</div><br />The first item on <a href="https://www.lua.org/manual/5.3/readme.html#changes" class="postlink">the &quot;main changes&quot; list for Lua 5.3</a> is &quot;integers (64-bit by default)&quot;. Since your next point mentions requiring Lua 5.3 for bit ops...<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">No bitwise operators prior to 5.3. Data converters tend to need them, particular when CHR data and compression are involved.</div><br /><a href="http://lua-users.org/wiki/BitwiseOperators" class="postlink">Various solutions exist for this</a>, even for versions before 5.3.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What's the widely used counterpart to Pillow, the Python imaging library?</div><br />Based on <a href="https://luarocks.org/labels/image" class="postlink">number of downloads</a> from LuaRocks (think something like Perl's CPAN, but for Lua), the most used library is a wrapper for imlib2 named <a href="https://luarocks.org/modules/luarocks/lua-imlib2" class="postlink">lua-imlib2</a>.<br /><br />Other solutions are available from <a href="http://lua-users.org/wiki/LibrariesAndBindings" class="postlink">the lua-users wiki</a> (&quot;Image Manipulation&quot; section).</div>

