						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">thefox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">To add to the list of complaints, if you forget <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">local</tt> when defining a variable, it will define a global variable (or modify an existing one) instead.</div><br />JavaScript without <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">&quot;use strict&quot;</tt> has the same problem. So do C and C++ if a global variable happens to have the same name and type as the local variable you forgot to declare. For comparison, in Python, global variables are read-only without the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">global</tt> keyword, and in PHP, global variables aren't even in scope without the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">global</tt> keyword unless they're variables defined by the interpreter (mostly <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$_REQUEST</tt> and <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$_SERVER</tt>).</div>

